  <brief_title>Evaluating the Patient-Ventilator Synchrony During Mechanical Ventilation in Patients With Acute Lung Injury</brief_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>University of Chicago</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>University of Chicago</source>
  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The overall purpose to the study is to prospectively study how often patients with and
      without acute lung injury (ALI) have patient-ventilator asynchrony demonstrated as stacked
      breaths. The investigators seek to describe the quantity of stacked breaths by continuously
      recording flow, volume, and pressure waveforms routinely displayed on the vent. The
      investigators also seek to describe how primary ICU teams manage asynchrony documenting
      interventions of sedation or vent manipulation and what modality is most successful.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
